photo.description: Leaf A2 (recto visible) from Schatzbehalter der wahren Reichtümer des Heils by Stephan Fridolin, O.F.M., printed in Nuremberg by Anton Koberger on 8 November 1491 (ISTC is00306000). Cf. the facsimile ed. published as Schatzbehalter, v. 28 in the series The Printed Sources of Western Art, ed. T. Besterman (Portland, Or.: Collegium Graphicum, 1972). Established heading: Koberger, Anton, approximately 1440-1513 Median folio (?) [leaf size: 311 x 213 mm.], printed in double columns. Leaf A2r: 40 lines to a full column, plus headline ("Von de[n] haupt vnsers herren"); area of text: 246 (260) x 156 mm.; col. width: 73 mm. Two 2-line initial spaces, 1 with visible guide letter (1 initial supplied in blue and 1 in red). Spaces for 2 paragraph marks (supplied in red; section headings read: "Von dem achtundneuntzigsten gegenwurff." and "Der erst artickel des achtundneüntzigste[n] gegenwurffs."). (Capital strokes supplied in red.) With signature ("A ij"); without foliation or catchword. Penn Libraries call number: GC5 B2834 505r 1512 All images from this book

photo.title: Henry Elford Luxmoore (1841-1926); Austin Lamont (1905-1969)
photo.description: H.E. Luxmoore Everdon Rectory 10 April 1866 Ownership inscription of Henry Elford Luxmoore (1841-1926) Lower inscription: A. Lamont Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Penn Libraries call number: LatC C4855.10 1546 All images from this book

photo.title: Ornamental woodcut border with images of biblical scenes (Adam and Eve's creation, Temptation and Fall from Paradise), angels, David and Moses
photo.description:
Ornamental woodcut border with images of biblical scenes (Adam and Eve's creation, Temptation and Fall from Paradise), angels, David and Moses.


Contains the author's L' Acerba, an allegorical poem of encyclopedic range, consisting of four books. The first book treats of astronomy and meteorology; the second deals with stellar influences, physiognomy, vices and virtues; the third with minerals and the love of animals; and the fourth propounds and solves a number of moral and physical problems.

Text is illustrated with 77 woodcuts, depicting astronomical knowledge, women (illustrating vices and virtues), and dozens of woodcuts of animals.

The author was eventually burned at stake in 1327 for his defense of astrology and other subjects that were considered dangerous by the Inquisition.


Penn Libraries call number: IC C3230 476a 1514

tag.raw: Abbazia di Santa Maria di Pinerolo

photo.description:
Ex libris Mon[aste]rij B[ea]tae Mariae de Pinerolio.
Congregationis Reformato[rum] S[anc]ti Bernardi
[Abbazia di Santa Maria di Pinerolo, a Cistercian house after 1589 or 1590? -- the change appears to be associated with the abbacy commendatario [meaning he got the income of the abbey, but didn't actually live there and run it] of Vincenzo Lauro (also cardinal and bishop of Mondovi) but the date needs more research. Prior to that it was a Benedictine foundation. St. Francis de Sales visited it in 1621.]

photo.description: Prof. Osiander Gött[ingen] 1800 Probably Friedrich Benjamin Osiander (1759-1822), professor of gynecology and obstetrics at Göttingen and director of its lying-in hospital from 1792 until his death. photo.title: Printed music binding waste, possibly from an antiphonary
photo.description:
Possibly from an antiphonary; contains music and text for antiphon ("Num qui redditur pro bono malum, quia foderunt foveam animae meae"), notation for chanting its associated psalm, and music and text for hymn ("Lustra sex qui iam peregit" -- a portion of the "Pange Lingua" of Fortunatus, here as revised by Pope Urban VIII) associated with lauds of Passion Sunday. Probably not earlier than 1632, when Urban's revisions to the breviary were first published.

Penn Libraries call number: GrC Ar466 T3 1503 Folio

photo.title: Printed music binding waste, possibly from an antiphonary
photo.description:
Possibly from an antiphonary; contains music and text for antiphons associated with lauds of Passion Sunday: "In tribulatione invocavi Dominum et exaudivit me in latitudinem"; "Judicasti, Domine, causam animae meae, defensor vitae meae, Domine Deus meus"; and "Popule meus, quid feci tibi, aut quid molestus fui? responde mihi". Also contains notation for chanting their associated psalms. Probably not earlier than 1632; cf. its fellow for justification.

Penn Libraries call number: GrC Ar466 T3 1503 Folio
